The main issue is that when a function is passed as a callback is is executed in the context
of your child component. The magic `this` keyword in Javascript will point to the child component in that case.

Furthermore, it is not a good practice to use `@Input` for passing a callback.

You can solve the issue two ways:

First, I suggest to use common practices and leverage `@Output` to notify about events from child components.
To apply this method in your code you may refactor it as follows:

    @Component({
      selector: &#39;product-grid-item&#39;,
      styleUrls: [&#39;./product.grid.item.component.scss&#39;],
      templateUrl: &#39;./product.grid.item.component.html&#39;,
    })
    export class ProductGridItemComponent {
      @Input()
      item: Product;

      @Output()
      onItemClick: EventEmitter&lt;Product&gt; = new EventEmitter&lt;Product&gt;();

      constructor() {
      }

      onProductEditClick() {
        this.onItemClick.emit(this.item);
      }
    }

In your parent component:

    class=&quot;col-md-6 col-xl-4&quot; (onItemEditClick)=&quot;onProductEditClick($event)&quot; [item]=&quot;productItem&quot;&gt;

The second way is to create a binded function and pass it as callback:

    public boundedClickListener: Function;

    public ngOnInit(){
        this.boundedClickListener = this.onProductEditClick.bind(this);
    }

This will create a function bounded to the parent context.

However, as I&#39;ve already noted, I suggest to follow the first way.

Hope that will help to understand the issue.

